The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Tuesday, November 15, 2005 

 Jails put on alert

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Calcutta, Nov. 14: Alarmed at last nights incident in which armed extremists attacked Jehanabad jail and freed a large number of Maoists after killing some inmates, Buddhadeb Bhattacharjees government today put six jails across Bengal on alert.

 Several CPI(ML) and KLO activists are lodged in the Midnapore, Bankura, Purulia and Jalpaiguri jails and two central jails in Calcutta ? Alipore and Presidency.

 In the wake of the Jehanabad jail attack, we have alerted all the jails in which CPI(ML) and KLO activists have been lodged, said state home secretary Prasad Ranjan Roy. District magistrates and police chiefs had been asked to step up security in the six sensitive jails. He discussed security arrangements in all 54 jails across Bengal with secretary for jails P.K. Agrawal.

 The inspector general of police, law and order, Raj Kanojia, spoke to senior district police officials to assess security in the jails. The border districts of West Midnapore, Bankura and Purulia have been alerted.

 State minister for jails and social welfare Biswanath Chowdhury, who held discussions with the home secretary and the director general of police, S.C. Avasthy, said a jammer is being installed at the Alipore central jail at a cost of Rs 18 to 20 crore. Besides, close circuit cameras are being installed in the Midnapore and Behrampore central jails.

 Sources said Kanojia was told that watch-towers from where security staff monitor movements of the inmates are not properly manned. Moreover, there is hardly any round-the-clock patrolling. We have reinforced the watch towers and asked all jail superintendents to put its warders on high alert, said a deputy inspector general of prisons.




